      "source": [
        "#### Insight C — Risk-flagging is a *literacy* signal, not a *skepticism* signal\n",
        "\n",
        "The mainstream framing assumes that flagging more AI risks correlates with being more anti-AI. The data flatly contradicts this.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Heavy Adopters** flag bias risk at **64%**. The **Literacy Gap** cohort (people who explicitly say \"I don't understand AI\") flag it at **39%**. The most engaged AI users worry *more* about AI's risks than the unsure cohort does.\n",
        "\n",
        "**True AI Resisters** — the small group of actual AI opponents — flag every risk at the highest rates of all (84% for data breaches, 74% for bias). That's not the same population as the Literacy Gap. They understand AI, they've evaluated it, and they've decided no.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Implication:** \"non-user\" isn't a single audience. The AI Resister needs a different conversation than the Literacy Gap respondent — and crowding them together (as the published cluster does) loses the entire signal."
      ]
    },
