        "\n",
        "## 9. Deep dive — *The Latent Adopter*\n",
        "\n",
        "> *\"I'm not really familiar with AI — I want to learn.\"*  \n",
        "> *\"Allow us to automate and free up employee time.\"*  \n",
        "> *\"I worry the nonprofit sector will lag so far behind the private sector that the gaps will grow exponentially.\"*\n",
        "\n",
        "This section is one finding, deeply mined. We isolate a single 67-person cohort — the **Latent Adopters** — and ask: who are they, what do they want, what's blocking them, and *why does this matter for the field*?\n",
        "\n",
        "The short version: these are the people the deck's \"infrastructure\" thesis is actually about. They have the comfort, they have the aspiration, they have the partial scaffolding — but they're trying to do a fundamentally different kind of AI work than the Heavy Adopters have done, and the existing ecosystem isn't built to support it.\n",
        "\n",
        "### 9.1 Define the cohort\n",
        "\n",
        "A Latent Adopter is a respondent who:\n",
        "- is **not currently using AI**\n",
        "- self-rates AI comfort at **7+ out of 10** (high)\n",
        "- wants AI for **3 or more** specific use cases (high aspiration)\n",
        "\n",
        "We compare them against **Heavy Adopters** (using 4+ AI tools today) and the **Literacy Gap** cohort (non-users who picked *\"I don't understand AI enough\"* on the risk-reward question).\n"
