      "source": [
        "### 9.6 Why this matters for the field\n",
        "\n",
        "**This is the cohort the funder/policy conversation should center on:**\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **They're not skeptics, not anti-AI, not under-resourced.** They show up with full demand.\n",
        "2. **Their demand is operational, not creative.** They want to organize, automate, predict.\n",
        "3. **They're stalled at the last mile** — partial infrastructure, no clear vendor path, no permission to start.\n",
        "4. **The current AI ecosystem isn't built for them.** Consumer tools (ChatGPT, Claude) handle creative use cases. Enterprise tools (Snowflake + Databricks + ML Ops) handle operational use cases for orgs at $50M+ scale. There's a missing middle.\n",
        "\n",
        "If the deck's headline is *\"the fight is over infrastructure,\"* the Latent Adopters are the proof. **They have most of the infrastructure already. What they're missing is a path through the last layer** — and no one is building it for the small-to-mid nonprofit.\n",
        "\n",
        "> The Latent Adopters are the people the field has been talking about without realizing it. They're the cohort whose demand most resembles the demand we need AI to solve in the *real economy*: organize, predict, automate. They're 7% of this sample. In a field of 1.5 million U.S. nonprofits alone, that's potentially **100,000 organizations** with full-throated demand and partial infrastructure, waiting for the last rung.\n",
        "\n",
        "> ChatGPT solved the easy half of nonprofit AI. The Latent Adopters are building the ramp to the hard half — and they're stuck one rung short.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n"
      ]
