        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 7. The takeaway\n",
        "\n",
        "Across 930 nonprofit respondents, the data tells a story that's more specific than "nonprofits need more AI." Current AI use is concentrated in creative work — content generation, chatbots, translation — which makes up 62% of all use mentions. But stated demand flips: 60% of what nonprofits say they want next is operational — organizing information, automating tasks, interpreting data, predicting outcomes. Every operational use case shows an unmet-demand gap of 35 points or more, while creative use cases have effectively closed.
That flip is the central finding. The first wave of nonprofit AI adoption rode on consumer tools that work without clean data, pipelines, or workflow integration. The next wave of demand requires exactly those things — and the products to deliver it haven't been built for organizations at nonprofit scale. Cluster mix, comfort levels, and infrastructure scores all reinforce this read: the constraint isn't attitude (true AI resisters are 4% of the sample, not 15%), and it isn't enthusiasm (high-comfort non-users look identical to heavy adopters on aspiration). The constraint is that the operational tier of AI doesn't yet have a delivery path into the small-to-mid nonprofit.
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "*Source: GivingTuesday AI Readiness Survey 2024 · n=930 nonprofit respondents · 6 continents.*\n"
      ]
